# Data Science Practicals — Complete Theory Revision Notes

These are short, viva-friendly revision notes for all practicals.

---

# Practical 1 — Data Wrangling I

# MAIN TOPICS

* Data preprocessing
* Missing values
* Data formatting
* Normalization
* Encoding categorical variables

---

# IMPORTANT THEORY

# Data Wrangling

Process of cleaning and preparing raw data.

---

# Missing Values

Missing/empty data in dataset.

Detected using:

```python id="rev1"
isnull()
```

---

# describe()

Provides:

* mean
* std
* min
* max
* quartiles

---

# Data Types

| Type   | Example    |
| ------ | ---------- |
| int    | 10         |
| float  | 10.5       |
| object | text       |
| bool   | True/False |

---

# Normalization

Scaling values into range:

```text id="rev2"
0 to 1
```

Formula:

```text id="rev3"
(x-min)/(max-min)
```

---

# Encoding

Converting categorical data into numerical form.

Example:

```text id="rev4"
male → 0
female → 1
```

---

# REAL LIFE USE

* ML preprocessing
* banking
* healthcare

---

# Practical 2 — Data Wrangling II

# MAIN TOPICS

* Missing values
* Outlier detection
* Data transformation

---

# IMPORTANT THEORY

# Inconsistency

Invalid/unrealistic data.

Example:

```text id="rev5"
Attendance = 110%
```

---

# Outlier

Extreme unusual value.

Detected using:

# IQR Method

Formula:

```text id="rev6"
IQR = Q3 - Q1
```

Outlier range:

```text id="rev7"
Q1 - 1.5×IQR
Q3 + 1.5×IQR
```

---

# Data Transformation

Changing scale/distribution of data.

Example:

* normalization
* logarithmic transformation

---

# PURPOSE

* reduce skewness
* improve ML performance

---

# Practical 3 — Descriptive Statistics

# MAIN TOPICS

* Mean
* Median
* Standard deviation
* Percentiles
* Grouping

---

# IMPORTANT THEORY

# Mean

Average value.

---

# Median

Middle value.

---

# Standard Deviation

Measures spread of data.

Low std:
data close together.

High std:
data spread apart.

---

# Percentile

Value below certain percentage.

Example:

```text id="rev8"
75th percentile
```

---

# groupby()

Groups data category-wise.

---

# Iris Dataset

Famous ML dataset with:

* setosa
* versicolor
* virginica

---

# Practical 4 — Linear Regression

# MAIN TOPICS

* Supervised learning
* Regression
* Prediction
* Model evaluation

---

# IMPORTANT THEORY

# Linear Regression

Predicts continuous numerical values.

Equation:

```text id="rev9"
y = mx + c
```

---

# Features

Input variables.

---

# Target Variable

Output variable.

---

# Train-Test Split

* training data
* testing data

---

# fit()

Trains model.

---

# predict()

Generates predictions.

---

# MSE

Mean Squared Error.

Lower MSE = better model.

---

# R² Score

Model accuracy measure.

Range:

```text id="rev10"
0 to 1
```

---

# REAL LIFE USE

* house price prediction
* sales forecasting

---

# Practical 5 — Logistic Regression

# MAIN TOPICS

* Classification
* Confusion matrix
* Accuracy metrics

---

# IMPORTANT THEORY

# Logistic Regression

Classification algorithm.

Used for:

```text id="rev11"
0 or 1 prediction
```

---

# Feature Scaling

Brings values into similar range.

Used:

```python id="rev12"
StandardScaler()
```

---

# Sigmoid Function

Outputs probability between:

```text id="rev13"
0 and 1
```

---

# Confusion Matrix

| Term | Meaning          |
| ---- | ---------------- |
| TP   | correct positive |
| TN   | correct negative |
| FP   | false positive   |
| FN   | false negative   |

---

# Accuracy

Correct predictions/total.

---

# Precision

Correct positive predictions.

---

# Recall

Ability to detect positives.

---

# REAL LIFE USE

* spam detection
* disease prediction

---

# Practical 6 — Naïve Bayes

# MAIN TOPICS

* Probability
* Bayes theorem
* Classification

---

# IMPORTANT THEORY

# Naïve Bayes

Probability-based classifier.

---

# Bayes Theorem

```text id="rev14"
P(A|B)=P(B|A)×P(A)/P(B)
```

---

# “Naïve”

Assumes features are independent.

---

# GaussianNB

Used for continuous numerical data.

---

# Advantages

* fast
* simple
* efficient

---

# REAL LIFE USE

* spam filtering
* recommendation systems

---

# Practical 7 — Text Analytics

# MAIN TOPICS

* NLP
* Tokenization
* Stemming
* Lemmatization
* TF-IDF

---

# IMPORTANT THEORY

# NLP

Natural Language Processing.

Helps computers understand language.

---

# Tokenization

Breaking text into tokens.

---

# POS Tagging

Assigning grammatical tags.

Example:

```text id="rev15"
noun
verb
adjective
```

---

# Stopwords

Common words:

```text id="rev16"
is
the
and
```

---

# Stemming

Reducing words to root.

Example:

```text id="rev17"
playing → play
```

---

# Lemmatization

Converting into dictionary word.

---

# TF

Term Frequency.

---

# IDF

Inverse Document Frequency.

---

# TF-IDF

Measures word importance.

---

# REAL LIFE USE

* ChatGPT
* search engines
* sentiment analysis

---

